   <text>
      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0984">
               <p>Usually called &apos;John&apos;, this former Jacobite, had aligned with Methodism
                  in <placeName>Newcastle</placeName> by early <date when="1743">1743</date>, when
                  he served as a guide to <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> (see <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName>, <hi rend="italic">Journal</hi>, <date when="1743-04-01">Apr.
                     1, 1743</date>, <hi rend="italic">Works</hi>, 19:321). He had a tendency to
                  defend the cause physically, leading <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"
                     />CW</persName> to send him out of <placeName>Newcastle</placeName> on <date
                     when="1744-02-19">Feb. 19, 1744</date> to avoid a mob (see <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName>, MS Journal). Healey moved to
                     <placeName>Nottingham</placeName> and was arrested there on <date
                     when="1744-03-10">Mar. 10</date> as a Methodist sympathizer. He appears to have
                  continued to assist the Wesley brothers from that point, though his name does not
                  appear in the Minutes as a preacher. In <date when="1747-10">Oct. 1747</date>
                  <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName> appealed to
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> for Healey to
                  be sent to <placeName>Ireland</placeName>. There he suffered the attack of a mob
                  and was rescued by <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName> in
                     <date when="1748-02">Feb. 1748</date>. By <date when="1749-05">May 1749</date>
                  he was back in <placeName>England</placeName>, causing concern again for
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName> by physical
                  threats against the opponents of Methodism. On <date when="1749-07-06">July 6,
                     1749</date>, <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName>
                  finally put him out of the society for beating a mentally-unstable elderly man
                  (see MS Journal).</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
